article.headline: Stanford 39, Washington State 37
article.story: PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- Stanford and Washington State played the lowest-scoring Pac-10 game in 22 years on Saturday, and Stanford coach Trent Johnson said he wasn't surprised. "It's what you expect when you play a Dick Bennett-coached team," Johnson said after the Cardinal edged Washington State 39-37 on Anthony Goods' tip-in basket with 3.7 seconds left. "It was like a 1920's game," Stanford's Chris Hernandez said. Hernandez, whose 15-foot jump shot was tipped in by Goods for the deciding basket, led Stanford (14-11, 10-6 Pac-10) with 10 points. Josh Akognon led Washington State (11-14, 4-12) with 11 points, and Robbie Cowgill added 10. The 76 points was the lowest in a Pac-10 game since Oregon State defeated Oregon 29-23 prior to the shot clock on March 3, 1984. It was Stanford's lowest point total since 1981-82 and the lowest Stanford score in a win since 1946-47. "It was probably the lowest combined score of any game I've ever been in," Hernandez said. Hernandez, a senior with a well-earned reputation for making clutch shots in the final seconds, relinquished the hero's role to Goods on Saturday. Goods, a freshman reserve, played a season-high 22 minutes and scored five points to boost his season scoring average to 1.6. "I thought it was going to go in, but you can't just assume that," Goods said. Goods said he was shocked when no one boxed him out on his tip-in. Randy Green, who was honored prior to the game as Washington's lone senior, said he was responsible for boxing out Goods. "You've got to stay alert at all times, and I kind of fell asleep," Green said. Green, who made a rare start and tied his career high with four steals, went scoreless on 0-for-7 shooting. Both teams shot just 33 percent from the field and combined for only 20 fouls and 12 free throws (two by Washington State) in a rugged contest. "The refs let us play," Cowgill said. Bennett, who is expected to retire next month after 39 years of coaching, was praised at length by Johnson. "He's one of the best -- he's one of our icons," Johnson said. "He's humble and unassuming." The Cougars are last in the Pac-10 in offense, but first in defense. That's standard for a Bennett team. "You won't see us play any better defense," Bennett said after his team fell to 0-5 in two-point games. "This is a team I've been critical of defensively, but they rose to the occasion." Washington State led 22-20 at the half, but went six minutes without a point in the second half. At one point, neither team scored in nearly five minutes in the second half. "It's hard to get in the flow on offense against such a good defensive team," Hernandez said. WSU tied the game at 37-37 when Cowgill spun and banged his way through the lane on a drive with 1:02 left. Stanford's Matt Haryasz missed a shot with 35 seconds left, but the ball went out of bounds off a Cougar. Washington State's Derrick Low missed a long, hurried 3-pointer at the final horn.
